# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: angular
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:angular/angular-web-framework] Google designed Angular as a ground-up rewrite of AngularJS.
[src:angular/angular-web-framework] Unlike AngularJS, Angular does not have a concept of "scope" or controllers; instead, it uses a hierarchy of components as its primary architectural characteristic.
[src:angular/angular-web-framework] Angular has a different expression syntax, focusing on `"[ ]"` for property binding, and `"( )"` for event binding.
[src:angular/angular-web-framework] Angular recommends the use of Microsoft's TypeScript language, which introduces features such as static typing, generics, and type annotations.
[src:angular/angular-web-framework] Angular uses a component-based architecture, which allows developers to build encapsulated, reusable user interface elements.
[src:angular/angular-web-framework] Each component encapsulates its own HTML, CSS, and TypeScript, making it easier to manage and test individual pieces of an application.
[src:angular/angular-web-framework] Angular supports two-way data binding which synchronizes data between the model and the view.
[src:angular/angular-web-framework] This ensures that any changes in the view are automatically reflected in the model and vice versa.
[src:angular/angular-web-framework] Angular has a built-in dependency injection system that makes it easier to manage and inject dependencies into components and services.
[src:angular/angular-web-framework] This promotes modularity and easier testing.
[src:angular/angular-web-framework] Angular extends HTML with additional attributes called directives.
[src:angular/angular-web-framework] Directives offer functionality to change the behavior or appearance of DOM elements.
[src:angular/angular-web-framework] Angular includes a router that allows developers to define and manage application states and navigation paths, making it easier to build single-page applications with complex routing.
[src:angular/angular-web-framework] The Angular CLI (Command Line Interface) provides a set of tools for creating, building, testing, and deploying Angular applications.
[src:angular/angular-web-framework] It enables rapid application setup and simplifies ongoing development tasks.
[src:angular/angular-web-framework] Angular has official support for server-side rendering, which improves an application's load time and performance.
[src:angular/angular-web-framework] Server-side rendering also enhances search engine optimization by making content more accessible to web crawlers.
[src:angular/angular-web-framework] Angular 2.0 was announced during the keynote of the 2014 NG-Conf conference 16–17 January 2014.
[src:angular/angular-web-framework] On April 30, 2015, the Angular developers announced that Angular 2 moved from Alpha to Developer Preview.
[src:angular/angular-web-framework] Angular 2 moved to Beta in December 2015, and the first release candidate was published in May 2016.
[src:angular/angular-web-framework] The final version was released on 14 September 2016.
[src:angular/angular-web-framework] Version 8 of Angular introduced a new compilation and rendering pipeline, Ivy, and version 9 of Angular enabled Ivy by default.
[src:angular/angular-web-framework] Angular 13 removed the deprecated former compiler, View Engine.
[src:angular/angular-web-framework] Angular 14 introduced standalone components and Angular 17 made them the default, de-emphasizing the use of modules.
[src:angular/angular-web-framework] The rewrite of AngularJS was called "Angular 2", but this led to confusion among developers.
[src:angular/angular-web-framework] To clarify, the team announced that separate names should be used for each framework with "AngularJS" referring to the 1.X versions and "Angular" without the "JS" referring to versions 2 and up.
[src:angular/angular-web-framework] Since v9, the Angular team has moved all new applications to use the Ivy compiler and runtime.
[src:angular/angular-web-framework] They will be working on Ivy to improve output bundle sizes and development speeds.
[src:angular/angular-web-framework] Each version is expected to be backward-compatible with the prior release.
[src:angular/angular-web-framework] The Angular development team has pledged to do twice-a-year upgrades.
[src:angular/angular-web-framework] All the major releases are supported for 18 months.
[src:angular/angular-web-framework] This consists of 6 months of active support, during which regularly scheduled updates and patches are released.
[src:angular/angular-web-framework] It is then followed by 12 months of long-term support (LTS), during which only critical fixes and security patches are released.
[src:angular/angular-web-framework] Angular versions v2 to v19 are no longer under support.
[src:angular/angular-web-framework] Analog is a full stack web meta-framework based upon Angular powered by Vite and Nitro.
[src:angular/angular-web-framework] Angular Material is a UI component library that implements Material Design in Angular.
[src:angular/angular-web-framework] It provides a collection of reusable components that adhere to Google's Material Design specifications, aiming to offer a consistent user interface across different devices and platforms.
[src:angular/angular-web-framework] Angular Material includes a variety of UI components such as buttons, cards, dialogs, grids, and form controls.
[src:angular/angular-web-framework] These components are designed to be customizable and easy to integrate into Angular applications.
[src:angular/angular-web-framework] Additional features of Angular Material include support for responsive design, theming, and accessibility.
[src:angular/angular-web-framework] In 2018, Angular 6 introduced Angular Elements, enabling developers to package Angular components as custom web elements, which are part of the web components set of web platform APIs.
[src:angular/angularjs] AngularJS was used as the frontend of the MEAN stack, that consisted of MongoDB database, Express.js web application server framework, AngularJS itself (or Angular), and Node.js server runtime environment.
[src:angular/angularjs] As of January 1, 2022, Google no longer updates AngularJS to fix security, browser compatibility, or jQuery issues.
[src:angular/angularjs] The Angular team recommends upgrading to Angular (v2+) as the best path forward, but they also provided some other options.
[src:angular/angularjs] The AngularJS framework worked by first reading the HyperText Markup Language (HTML) page, which had additional custom HTML attributes embedded into it.
[src:angular/angularjs] Angular interpreted those attributes as directives to bind input or output parts of the page to a model that is represented by standard JavaScript variables.
[src:angular/angularjs] The values of those JavaScript variables could be manually set within the code or retrieved from static or dynamic JSON resources.
[src:angular/angularjs] AngularJS was built on the belief that declarative programming should be used to create user interfaces and connect software components, while imperative programming was better suited to defining an application's business logic.
[src:angular/angularjs] The framework adapted and extended traditional HTML to present dynamic content through two-way data-binding that allowed for the automatic synchronization of models and views.
[src:angular/angularjs] As a result, AngularJS de-emphasized explicit Document Object Model (DOM) manipulation with the goal of improving testability and performance.
[src:angular/angularjs] AngularJS implemented the MVC pattern to separate presentation, data, and logic components.
[src:angular/angularjs] Using dependency injection, Angular brought traditionally server-side services, such as view-dependent controllers, to client-side web applications.
[src:angular/angularjs] Consequently, much of the burden on the server could be reduced.
[src:angular/angularjs] AngularJS used the term "scope" in a manner akin to the fundamentals of computer science.
[src:angular/angularjs] Scope in computer science describes when in the program a particular binding is valid.
[src:angular/angularjs] The ECMA-262 specification defines scope as: a lexical environment in which a Function object is executed in client-side web scripts; akin to how scope is defined in lambda calculus.
[src:angular/angularjs] As a part of the "MVC" architecture, the scope forms the "Model", and all variables defined in the scope can be accessed by the "View" as well as the "Controller".
[src:angular/angularjs] The scope behaves as a glue and binds the "View" and the "Controller".
[src:angular/angularjs] AngularJS directives allowed the developer to specify custom and reusable HTML-like elements and attributes that define data bindings and the behavior of presentation components.
[src:angular/angularjs] A module provides support for JavaScript, CSS3 transition and CSS3 keyframe animation hooks within existing core and custom directives.
