[src:angular/angularjs] AngularJS was originally developed in 2009 by Miško Hevery at Brat Tech LLC as the software behind an online JSON storage service, that would have been priced by the megabyte, for easy-to-make applications for the enterprise.
[src:angular/angularjs] This venture was located at the web domain "GetAngular.com", and had a few subscribers, before the two decided to abandon the business idea and release Angular as an open-source library.
[src:angular/angularjs] The 1.6 release added many of the concepts of Angular to AngularJS, including the concept of a component-based application architecture.
[src:angular/angularjs] This release among others removed the Sandbox, which many developers believed provided additional security, despite numerous vulnerabilities that had been discovered that bypassed the sandbox.
[src:angular/angularjs] In January 2018, a schedule was announced for phasing-out AngularJS: after releasing 1.7.0, the active development on AngularJS would continue until June 30, 2018.
[src:angular/angularjs] Afterwards, 1.7 was supported until December 31, 2021 as long-term support.
[src:angular/angularjs] Versions 1.3 and later of AngularJS did not support Internet Explorer 8 or earlier.
[src:angular/angularjs] While AngularJS 1.2 supported IE8, its team does not.
[src:angular/angularjs] Subsequent versions of AngularJS are simply called Angular.
[src:angular/angularjs] Angular is an incompatible TypeScript-based rewrite of AngularJS.
[src:angular/angularjs] Angular 4 was announced on 13 December 2016, skipping 3 to avoid a confusion due to the misalignment of the router package's version which was already distributed as v3.3.0.
[src:angular/angularjs] AngularDart works on Dart, which is an object-oriented, class-based, and single inheritance programming language using C-style syntax.
[src:angular/angularjs] This differs from AngularJS (which uses JavaScript) and later versions of Angular such as Angular 2 and Angular 4 (which use TypeScript).
[src:angular/angularjs] Angular 4 was released in March 2017, with the framework's version aligned with the version number of the router it used.
[src:angular/angularjs] Angular 5 was released on November 1, 2017.
[src:angular/angularjs] Key improvements in Angular 5 include support for progressive web applications, a build optimizer, and enhancements related to Material Design.
[src:angular/angularjs] Angular 6 was released on May 3, 2018, followed by Angular 7 on October 18, 2018, and Angular 8 on May 28, 2019.
[src:angular/angularjs] Angular follows Semantic Versioning standards, with each major version number indicating potentially breaking changes.
[src:angular/angularjs] Angular has pledged to provide 6 months of active support for each major version followed by 12 months of long-term support.
[src:angular/angularjs] Major releases are bi-yearly with 1 to 3 minor releases for every major release.
[src:angular/angularjs] A normal Angular application executes in the browser, while Angular Universal generates static application pages on the server through server-side rendering (SSR).
[src:angular/angularjs] AngularJS Material was a UI component library that implemented Material Design in AngularJS.
[src:angular/angularjs] The library provided a set of reusable, well-tested, and accessible UI components.
[src:angular/angularjs] In January 2022, the library was closed, as announced on their official website.
[src:angular/angularjs] The AngularJS Material library is a mature and stable product that is ready for production use and works only with AngularJS 1.x.
[src:angular/angularjs] The Angular Material library is available in the angular/material2 GitHub repository.
[src:angular/angularjs] In July 2012, the Angular team built an extension for the Google Chrome browser called Batarang, that improved the debugging experience for web applications built with Angular.
[src:angular/angularjs] The extension aimed to allow for easy detection of performance bottlenecks and offered a GUI for debugging applications.
[src:angular/angularjs] For a time during late 2014 and early 2015, the extension was not compatible with recent releases (after v1.2.x) of Angular.
[src:angular/angularjs] The last update made to this extension was on April 4, 2017.
[src:angular/angularjs] Additionally, the extension was removed from the Chrome Web Store on June 1, 2022, due to its lack of updates and potential security concerns, such as requiring sensitive permissions.
[src:angular/angularjs] AngularJS set out the paradigm of a *digest cycle*.
[src:angular/angularjs] This cycle could be considered a loop, during which AngularJS checked if there were any changes to all the variables watched by all the `$scopes`.
[src:angular/angularjs] If `$scope.myVar` is defined in a controller and this variable was marked for watching, Angular would monitor the changes on myVar in each loop iteration.
[src:angular/angularjs] This approach potentially led to slow rendering when AngularJS checked on too many variables in the `$scope` every cycle.
[src:angular/angularjs] Miško Hevery suggested keeping fewer than 2000 watchers on any page.
[src:angular/frameworks-libraries] JavaScript frameworks are an essential part of modern front-end web development, providing developers with tried and tested tools for building scalable, interactive web applications.
[src:angular/frameworks-libraries] Many modern companies use frameworks as a standard part of their tooling, so many front-end development jobs now require framework experience.
[src:angular/frameworks-libraries] This set of articles provides a comfortable starting point to help you begin learning frameworks.
[src:angular/frameworks-libraries] We are not aiming to exhaustively teach you everything you need to know about React/ReactDOM, or Vue, or some other specific framework; the framework teams' own docs (and other resources) do that job already.
[src:angular/frameworks-libraries] After that, we'll provide some tutorials covering the essentials React, a popular framework choice, to provide you with enough context and familiarity to start going into greater depth yourself.
[src:angular/frameworks-libraries] We want you to go forward and learn about frameworks in a pragmatic way that doesn't forget about web platform fundamental best practices such as accessibility.
[src:angular/frameworks-libraries] We also provide some tutorials covering the basics of other framework choices, for those who want to make a different choice to React.
[src:angular/frameworks-libraries] You should really learn the basics of the core web languages first before attempting to move on to learning client-side frameworks — HTML, CSS, and especially JavaScript.
[src:angular/frameworks-libraries] Your code will be richer and more professional as a result, and you'll be able to troubleshoot problems with more confidence if you understand the fundamental web platform features that the frameworks are building on top of.
[src:angular/frameworks-libraries] We begin our look at frameworks with a general overview of the area, looking at a brief history of JavaScript and frameworks, why frameworks exist and what they give us, how to start thinking about choosing a framework to learn, and what alternatives there are to client-side frameworks.
[src:angular/frameworks-libraries] Each major JavaScript framework has a different approach to updating the DOM, handling browser events, and providing an enjoyable developer experience.
[src:angular/frameworks-libraries] This article will explore the main features of "the big 4" frameworks, looking at how frameworks tend to work from a high level and the differences between them.
