[src:angular/single-page-application] A **single-page application** (**SPA**) is a web application or website that interacts with the user by dynamically rewriting the current web page with new data from the web server, instead of the default method of loading entire new pages.
[src:angular/single-page-application] The goal is faster transitions that make the website feel more like a native app.
[src:angular/single-page-application] In a SPA, a page refresh never occurs; instead, all necessary HTML, JavaScript, and CSS code is either retrieved by the browser with a single page load, or the appropriate resources are dynamically loaded and added to the page as necessary, usually in response to user actions.
[src:angular/single-page-application] The origins of the term *single-page application* are unclear, though the concept was discussed at least as early as 2003 by technology evangelists from Netscape.
[src:angular/single-page-application] Earlier forms were called rich web applications.
[src:angular/single-page-application] JavaScript can be used in a web browser to display the user interface (UI), run application logic, and communicate with a web server.
[src:angular/single-page-application] Mature free libraries are available that support the building of a SPA, reducing the amount of JavaScript code developers have to write.
[src:angular/single-page-application] There are various techniques available that enable the browser to retain a single page even when the application requires server communication.
[src:angular/single-page-application] HTML authors can leverage element IDs to show or hide different sections of the HTML document.
[src:angular/single-page-application] Then, using CSS, authors can use the `:target` pseudo-class selector to only show the section of the page which the browser navigated to.
[src:angular/single-page-application] Web browser JavaScript frameworks and libraries, such as Angular, Ember.js, ExtJS, Knockout.js, Meteor.js, React, Vue.js, and Svelte have adopted SPA principles.
[src:angular/single-page-application] Aside from ExtJS, all of these are free.
[src:angular/single-page-application] JavaScript-based web application frameworks, such as React and Vue, provide extensive capabilities but come with associated trade-offs.
[src:angular/single-page-application] These frameworks often extend or enhance features available through native web technologies, such as routing, component-based development, and state management.
[src:angular/single-page-application] Frameworks can introduce abstraction layers that may contribute to performance overhead, larger bundle sizes, and increased complexity.
[src:angular/single-page-application] Modern frameworks, such as React 18 and Vue 3, address these challenges with features like concurrent rendering, tree-shaking, and selective hydration.
[src:angular/single-page-application] While these advancements improve rendering efficiency and resource management, their benefits depend on the specific application and implementation context.
[src:angular/single-page-application] Lightweight frameworks, such as Svelte and Preact, take different architectural approaches, with Svelte eliminating the virtual DOM entirely in favor of compiling components to efficient JavaScript code, and Preact offering a minimal, compatible alternative to React.
[src:angular/single-page-application] Framework choice depends on an application’s requirements, including the team’s expertise, performance goals, and development priorities.
[src:angular/single-page-application] A newer category of web frameworks, including enhance.dev, Astro, and Fresh, leverages native web standards while minimizing abstractions and development tooling.
[src:angular/single-page-application] These solutions emphasize progressive enhancement, server-side rendering, and optimizing performance.
[src:angular/single-page-application] Astro renders static HTML by default while hydrating only interactive parts.
[src:angular/single-page-application] Fresh focuses on server-side rendering with zero runtime overhead.
[src:angular/single-page-application] Enhance.dev prioritizes progressive enhancement patterns using Web Components.
[src:angular/single-page-application] While these tools reduce reliance on client-side JavaScript by shifting logic to build-time or server-side execution, they still use JavaScript where necessary for interactivity.
[src:angular/single-page-application] This approach makes them particularly suitable for performance-critical and content-focused applications.
[src:angular/single-page-application] The following frameworks utilize WebAssembly or can build single-page applications (SPAs) with WebAssembly as a core technology or support mechanism.
[src:angular/single-page-application] These frameworks enable high-performance and interactive client-side development, extending the SPA paradigm across languages and ecosystems.
[src:angular/single-page-application] As of 2006, the most prominent technique used was Ajax.
[src:angular/single-page-application] Ajax involves using asynchronous requests to a server for XML or JSON data, such as with JavaScript's XMLHttpRequest or more modern `fetch()` (since 2017), or the deprecated ActiveX Object.
[src:angular/single-page-application] In contrast to the declarative approach of most SPA frameworks, with Ajax the website directly uses JavaScript or a JavaScript library such as jQuery to manipulate the DOM and edit HTML elements.
[src:angular/single-page-application] Ajax has further been popularized by libraries like jQuery, which provides a simpler syntax and normalizes Ajax behavior across different browsers which historically had varying behavior.
[src:angular/single-page-application] WebSockets are a bidirectional real-time client-server communication technology that are part of the HTML specification.
[src:angular/single-page-application] For real-time communication, their use is superior to Ajax in terms of performance and simplicity.
[src:angular/single-page-application] Server-sent events (SSEs) is a technique whereby servers can initiate data transmission to browser clients.
[src:angular/single-page-application] Once an initial connection has been established, an event stream remains open until closed by the client.
[src:angular/single-page-application] SSEs are sent over traditional HTTP and have a variety of features that WebSockets lack by design such as automatic reconnection, event IDs, and the ability to send arbitrary events.
[src:angular/single-page-application] Although this method is outdated, asynchronous calls to the server may also be achieved using browser plug-in technologies such as Silverlight, Flash, or Java applets.
[src:angular/single-page-application] Requests to the server typically result in either raw data (e.g., XML or JSON), or new HTML being returned.
[src:angular/single-page-application] In the case where HTML is returned by the server, JavaScript on the client updates a partial area of the DOM (Document Object Model).
[src:angular/single-page-application] When raw data is returned, JavaScript on the client translates it into HTML using XSL or a JSON template before updating the DOM.
[src:angular/single-page-application] A SPA moves logic from the server to the client, with the role of the web server evolving into a pure data API or web service.
[src:angular/single-page-application] This architectural shift has, in some circles, been coined "Thin Server Architecture" to highlight that complexity has been moved from the server to the client, with the argument that this ultimately reduces overall complexity of the system.
[src:angular/single-page-application] The server keeps the necessary state in memory of the client state of the page.
[src:angular/single-page-application] In this way, when any request hits the server (usually user actions), the server sends the appropriate HTML and/or JavaScript with the concrete changes to bring the client to the new desired state (usually adding/deleting/updating a part of the client DOM).
[src:angular/single-page-application] At the same time, the state in server is updated.
[src:angular/single-page-application] Most of the logic is executed on the server, and HTML is usually also rendered on the server.
[src:angular/single-page-application] In some ways, the server simulates a web browser, receiving events and performing delta changes in server state which are automatically propagated to client.
[src:angular/single-page-application] This is a variant of the stateful server approach.
[src:angular/single-page-application] The client page sends data representing its current state to the server, usually through Ajax requests.
[src:angular/single-page-application] This approach requires that more data be sent to the server and may require more computational resources per request to partially or fully reconstruct the client page state in the server.
[src:angular/single-page-application] At the same time, this approach is more easily scalable because there is no per-client page data kept in the server and, therefore, Ajax requests can be dispatched to different server nodes with no need for session data sharing or server affinity.
[src:angular/single-page-application] Some SPAs may be executed from a local file using the file URI scheme.
[src:angular/single-page-application] This gives users the ability to download the SPA from a server and run the file from a local storage device, without depending on server connectivity.
[src:angular/single-page-application] If such a SPA wants to store and update data, it must use browser-based Web Storage.
[src:angular/single-page-application] These applications benefit from advances available with HTML.
[src:angular/single-page-application] Because the SPA is an evolution away from the stateless page-redraw model that browsers were originally designed for, some new challenges have emerged.
[src:angular/single-page-application] Because of the lack of JavaScript execution on crawlers of some popular Web search engines, SEO (search engine optimization) has historically presented a problem for public facing websites wishing to adopt the SPA model.
[src:angular/single-page-application] Between 2009 and 2015, Google Webmaster Central proposed and then recommended an "AJAX crawling scheme" using an initial exclamation mark in fragment identifiers for stateful AJAX pages (`#!`).
[src:angular/single-page-application] Special behavior must be implemented by the SPA site to allow extraction of relevant metadata by the search engine's crawler.
[src:angular/single-page-application] For search engines that do not support this URL hash scheme, the hashed URLs of the SPA remain invisible.
[src:angular/single-page-application] These "hash-bang" URIs have been considered problematic by a number of writers including Jeni Tennison at the W3C because they make pages inaccessible to those who do not have JavaScript activated in their browser.
[src:angular/single-page-application] They also break HTTP referer headers as browsers are not allowed to send the fragment identifier in the Referer header.
[src:angular/single-page-application] In 2015, Google deprecated their hash-bang AJAX crawling proposal.
[src:angular/single-page-application] Alternatively, applications may render the first page load on the server and subsequent page updates on the client.
[src:angular/single-page-application] This is traditionally difficult, because the rendering code might need to be written in a different language or framework on the server and in the client.
[src:angular/single-page-application] Using logic-less templates, cross-compiling from one language to another, or using the same language on the server and the client may help to increase the amount of code that can be shared.
[src:angular/single-page-application] In 2018, Google introduced dynamic rendering as another option for sites wishing to offer crawlers a non-JavaScript heavy version of a page for indexing purposes.
[src:angular/single-page-application] Dynamic rendering switches between a version of a page that is rendered client-side and a pre-rendered version for specific user agents.
[src:angular/single-page-application] This approach involves your web server detecting crawlers (via the user agent) and routing them to a renderer, from which they are then served a simpler version of HTML content.
[src:angular/single-page-application] As of 2024, Google no longer recommends dynamic rendering, suggesting "server-side rendering, static rendering, or hydration" instead.
[src:angular/single-page-application] Because SEO compatibility is not trivial in SPAs, SPAs are commonly not used in a context where search engine indexing is either a requirement, or desirable.
[src:angular/single-page-application] Use cases include applications that surface private data hidden behind an authentication system.
[src:angular/single-page-application] In the cases where these applications are consumer products, often a classic "page redraw" model is used for the applications landing page and marketing site, which provides enough meta data for the application to appear as a hit in a search engine query.
[src:angular/single-page-application] Blogs, support forums, and other traditional page redraw artifacts often sit around the SPA that can seed search engines with relevant terms.
[src:angular/single-page-application] As of 2021 and Google specifically, SEO compatibility for a plain SPA is straightforward and requires just a few simple conditions to be met.
[src:angular/single-page-application] One way to increase the amount of code that can be shared between servers and clients is to use a logic-less template language like Mustache or Handlebars.
[src:angular/single-page-application] Such templates can be rendered from different host languages, such as Ruby on the server and JavaScript in the client.
[src:angular/single-page-application] However, merely sharing templates typically requires duplication of business logic used to choose the correct templates and populate them with data.
[src:angular/single-page-application] Rendering from templates may have negative performance effects when only updating a small portion of the page—such as the value of a text input within a large template.
[src:angular/single-page-application] Replacing an entire template might also disturb a user's selection or cursor position, where updating only the changed value might not.
[src:angular/single-page-application] To avoid these problems, applications can use UI data bindings or granular DOM manipulation to only update the appropriate parts of the page instead of re-rendering entire templates.
[src:angular/single-page-application] With a SPA being, by definition, "a single page", the model breaks the browser's design for page history navigation using the "forward" or "back" buttons.
[src:angular/single-page-application] This presents a usability impediment when a user presses the back button, expecting the previous screen state within the SPA, but instead, the application's single page unloads and the previous page in the browser's history is presented.
[src:angular/single-page-application] The traditional solution for SPAs has been to change the browser URL's hash fragment identifier in accord with the current screen state.
[src:angular/single-page-application] This can be achieved with JavaScript, and causes URL history events to be built up within the browser.
[src:angular/single-page-application] As long as the SPA is capable of resurrecting the same screen state from information contained within the URL hash, the expected back-button behavior is retained.
[src:angular/single-page-application] To further address this issue, the HTML specification has introduced pushState and replaceState providing programmatic access to the actual URL and browser history.
[src:angular/single-page-application] Analytics tools such as Google Analytics rely heavily upon entire new pages loading in the browser, initiated by a new page load.
[src:angular/single-page-application] After the first page load, all subsequent page and content changes are handled internally by the application, which should simply call a function to update the analytics package.
[src:angular/single-page-application] Failing to call such a function, the browser never triggers a new page load, nothing gets added to the browser history, and the analytics package has no idea who is doing what on the site.
[src:angular/single-page-application] Similarly to the problems encountered with search engine crawlers, DAST tools may struggle with these JavaScript-rich applications.
[src:angular/single-page-application] Problems can include the lack of hypertext links, memory usage concerns and resources loaded by the SPA typically being made available by an Application Programming Interface or API.
[src:angular/single-page-application] Single-page applications are still subject to the same security risks as traditional web pages such as Cross-Site Scripting (XSS), but also a host of other unique vulnerabilities such as data exposure via API and client-side logic and client-side enforcement of server-side security.
[src:angular/single-page-application] In order to effectively scan a single-page application, a DAST scanner must be able to navigate the client-side application in a reliable and repeatable manner to allow discovery of all areas of the application and interception of all requests that the application sends to remote servers (e.g.
[src:angular/single-page-application] It is possible to add page load events to a SPA using the HTML History API; this will help integrate analytics.
[src:angular/single-page-application] The difficulty comes in managing this and ensuring that everything is being tracked accurately – this involves checking for missing reports and double entries.
[src:angular/single-page-application] Some frameworks provide free analytics integrations addressing most of the major analytics providers.
[src:angular/single-page-application] Developers can integrate them into the application and make sure that everything is working correctly, but there is no need to do everything from scratch.
[src:angular/single-page-application] There are some ways of speeding up the initial load of a SPA, such as selective prerendering of the SPA landing/index page, caching and various code splitting techniques including lazy-loading modules when needed.
[src:angular/single-page-application] But it's not possible to get away from the fact that it needs to download the framework, at least some of the application code; and will hit an API for data if the page is dynamic.
[src:angular/single-page-application] This is a "pay me now, or pay me later" trade-off scenario.
[src:angular/single-page-application] The question of performance and wait-times remains a decision that the developer must make.
[src:angular/single-page-application] A SPA is fully loaded in the initial page load and then page regions are replaced or updated with new page fragments loaded from the server on demand.
[src:angular/single-page-application] To avoid excessive downloading of unused features, a SPA will often progressively download more features as they become required, either small fragments of the page, or complete screen modules.
[src:angular/single-page-application] In this way an analogy exists between "states" in a SPA and "pages" in a traditional website.
[src:angular/single-page-application] Because "state navigation" in the same page is analogous to page navigation, in theory, any page-based web site could be converted to single-page replacing in the same page only the changed parts.
[src:angular/single-page-application] The SPA approach on the web is similar to the single-document interface (SDI) presentation technique popular in native desktop applications.
[src:angular/web-framework] A **web framework** (**WF**), **web application framework** (**WAF**), or **web development framework** is a software framework that is designed to support the development of web applications including web services, web resources, and web APIs.
[src:angular/web-framework] Web frameworks provide a standard way to build and deploy web applications on the World Wide Web.
[src:angular/web-framework] Web frameworks aim to automate the overhead associated with common activities performed in web development.
[src:angular/web-framework] For example, many web frameworks provide libraries for database access, templating frameworks, and session management, and they often promote code reuse.
[src:angular/web-framework] Although they often target development of dynamic web sites, they are also applicable to static websites.
[src:angular/web-framework] As the design of the World Wide Web was not inherently dynamic, early hypertext consisted of hand-coded HTML text files that were published on web servers.
[src:angular/web-framework] Any modifications to published pages needed to be performed by the pages' author.
[src:angular/web-framework] In 1993, the Common Gateway Interface (CGI) standard was introduced for interfacing external applications with web servers, to provide a dynamic web page that reflected user inputs.
[src:angular/web-framework] Original implementations of the CGI interface typically had adverse effects on the server load however, because each request started a separate process.
[src:angular/web-framework] More recent implementations utilize persistent processes amongst other techniques to reduce the footprint in the server's resources and offer a general performance boost.
[src:angular/web-framework] In 1995, fully integrated server/language development environments first emerged and new web-specific languages were introduced, such as ColdFusion, PHP, and Active Server Pages.
[src:angular/web-framework] Although the vast majority of languages for creating dynamic web pages have libraries to help with common tasks, web applications often require specific libraries for particular tasks, such as creating HTML (for example, Jakarta Faces).
[src:angular/web-framework] In the late 1990s, mature, "full stack" frameworks began to appear, that often gathered multiple libraries useful for web development into a single cohesive software stack for web developers to use.
[src:angular/web-framework] Most web frameworks are based on the model–view–controller (MVC) pattern.
[src:angular/web-framework] Many frameworks follow the MVC architectural pattern to separate the data model into business rules (the "controller") and the user interface (the "view").
[src:angular/web-framework] This is generally considered a good practice as it modularizes code, promotes code reuse, and allows multiple interfaces to be applied.
[src:angular/web-framework] In web applications, this permits different views to be presented, for example serving different web pages for mobile vs. desktop browsers, or providing machine-readable web service interfaces.
[src:angular/web-framework] Most MVC frameworks follow a push-based architecture also called "action-based".
[src:angular/web-framework] These frameworks use actions that do the required processing, and then "push" the data to the view layer to render the results.
[src:angular/web-framework] An alternative to this is pull-based architecture, sometimes also called "component-based".
[src:angular/web-framework] These frameworks start with the view layer, which can then "pull" results from multiple controllers as needed.
[src:angular/web-framework] In this architecture, multiple controllers can be involved with a single view.
[src:angular/web-framework] In three-tier organization, applications are structured around three physical tiers: client, application, and database.
[src:angular/web-framework] The application contains the business logic, running on a server and communicates with the client using HTTP.
[src:angular/web-framework] The client on web applications is a web browser that runs HTML generated by the application layer.
[src:angular/web-framework] The term should not be confused with MVC, where, unlike in three-tier architecture, it is considered a good practice to keep business logic away from the controller, the "middle layer".
[src:angular/web-framework] Web frameworks must function according to the architectural rules of browsers and protocols such as HTTP, which is stateless.
[src:angular/web-framework] Webpages are served up by a server and can then be modified by the browser using JavaScript.
[src:angular/web-framework] Either approach has its advantages and disadvantages.
[src:angular/web-framework] Server-side page changes typically require that the page be refreshed, but allow any language to be used and more computing power to be utilized.
[src:angular/web-framework] Client-side changes allow the page to be updated in small chunks which feels like a desktop application, but are limited to JavaScript and run in the user's browser, which may have limited computing power.
[src:angular/web-framework] Applications which make heavy use of JavaScript and only refresh parts of the page, are called single-page applications and typically make use of a client-side JavaScript web framework to organize the code.
[src:angular/web-framework] Examples include Backbone.js, AngularJS, Angular, Ember.js, ReactJS, jQuery UI, Svelte, and Vue.js.
[src:angular/web-framework] Frameworks typically set the control flow of a program and allow the user of the framework to "hook into" that flow by exposing various events.
[src:angular/web-framework] This "inversion of control" design pattern is considered to be a defining principle of a framework, and benefits the code by enforcing a common flow for a team which everyone can customize in similar ways.
[src:angular/web-framework] For example, some popular "microframeworks" such as Ruby's Sinatra (which inspired Express.js) allow for "middleware" hooks prior to and after HTTP requests.
[src:angular/web-framework] These middleware functions can be anything, and allow the user to define logging, authentication and session management, and redirecting.
[src:angular/web-framework] Web caching is the caching of web documents in order to reduce bandwidth usage, server load, and perceived "lag".
[src:angular/web-framework] A web cache stores copies of documents passing through it; subsequent requests may be satisfied from the cache if certain conditions are met.
[src:angular/web-framework] Some application frameworks provide mechanisms for caching documents and bypassing various stages of the page's preparation, such as database access or template interpretation.
[src:angular/web-framework] Some web frameworks come with authentication and authorization frameworks, that enable the web server to identify the users of the application, and restrict access to functions based on some defined criteria.
[src:angular/web-framework] Drupal is one example that provides role-based access to pages, and provides a web-based interface for creating users and assigning them roles.
[src:angular/web-framework] Many web frameworks create a unified API to a database backend, enabling web applications to work with a variety of databases with no code changes, and allowing programmers to work with higher-level concepts.
[src:angular/web-framework] Additionally, some object-oriented frameworks contain mapping tools to provide object-relational mapping, which maps objects to tuples.
[src:angular/web-framework] Some frameworks minimize web application configuration through the use of introspection and/or following well-known conventions.
[src:angular/web-framework] For example, many Java frameworks use Hibernate as a persistence layer, which can generate a database schema at runtime capable of persisting the necessary information.
[src:angular/web-framework] This allows the application designer to design business objects without needing to explicitly define a database schema.
[src:angular/web-framework] Frameworks such as Ruby on Rails can also work in reverse, that is, define properties of model objects at runtime based on a database schema.
[src:angular/web-framework] Other features web frameworks may provide include transactional support and database migration tools.
[src:angular/web-framework] A framework's URL mapping or routing facility is the mechanism by which the framework interprets URLs.
[src:angular/web-framework] Some frameworks, such as Drupal and Django, match the provided URL against pre-determined patterns using regular expressions, while some others use rewriting techniques to translate the provided URL into one that the underlying engine will recognize.
[src:angular/web-framework] Another technique is that of graph traversal such as used by Zope, where a URL is decomposed in steps that traverse an object graph (of models and views).
[src:angular/web-framework] A URL mapping system that uses pattern matching or rewriting to route and handle requests allows for shorter more "friendly URLs" to be used, increasing the simplicity of the site and allowing for better indexing by search engines.
[src:angular/web-framework] For example, a URL that ends with "/page.cgi?cat=science&topic=physics" could be changed to simply "/page/science/physics".
[src:angular/web-framework] This makes the URL easier for people to remember, read and write, and provides search engines with better information about the structural layout of the site.
[src:angular/web-framework] A graph traversal approach also tends to result in the creation of friendly URLs.
[src:angular/web-framework] A shorter URL such as "/page/science" tends to exist by default as that is simply a shorter form of the longer traversal to "/page/science/physics".
[src:angular/web-framework] Ajax, shorthand for "*Asynchronous JavaScript and XML*", is a web development technique for creating web applications.
[src:angular/web-framework] The intent is to make web pages feel more responsive by exchanging small amounts of data with the server behind the scenes, so that the entire web page does not have to be reloaded each time the user requests a change.
[src:angular/web-framework] This is intended to increase a web page's interactivity, speed, maintainability, and usability.
[src:angular/web-framework] Due to the complexity of Ajax programming in JavaScript, there are numerous Ajax frameworks that exclusively deal with Ajax support.
[src:angular/web-framework] Some Ajax frameworks are even embedded as a part of larger frameworks.
[src:angular/web-framework] For example, the jQuery JavaScript library is included in Ruby on Rails.
[src:angular/web-framework] With the increased interest in developing "Web 2.0" rich web applications, the complexity of programming directly in Ajax and JavaScript has become so apparent that compiler technology has stepped in, to allow developers to code in high-level languages such as Java, Python and Ruby.
[src:angular/web-framework] The first of these compilers was Morfik followed by Google Web Toolkit, with ports to Python and Ruby in the form of Pyjs and RubyJS following some time after.
[src:angular/web-framework] These compilers and their associated widget set libraries make the development of rich media Ajax applications much more akin to that of developing desktop applications.
[src:angular/web-framework] Some frameworks provide tools for creating and providing web services.
[src:angular/web-framework] These utilities may offer similar tools as the rest of the web application.
[src:angular/web-framework] A number of newer Web 2.0 RESTful frameworks are now providing resource-oriented architecture (ROA) infrastructure for building collections of resources in a sort of Semantic Web ontology, based on concepts from Resource Description Framework (RDF).
